I think you’re pointing to something broader than any one organism: small-scale ecology is a library of operators. That’s a productive way to look at it.

At that scale, organisms aren’t simply “miniature versions” of larger animals. The governing constraints are different, so evolution discovers different strategies. A few examples:

* Nematodes — extreme simplicity with surprisingly effective sensing and navigation.
* Rotifers — compact, modular body plans that exploit transient environments.
* Slime molds — decentralized path finding and adaptive network formation without a central brain.
* Diatoms — intricate silica architectures that combine structure and function.
* Tardigrades — reversible state changes and reconstruction-first survival.
* Mites — specialized morphology tightly matched to ecological niches.

Each is solving a different optimization problem under the physics of that scale.

One abstraction that emerges is:

Morphology is an algorithm specialized to a medium.

The body isn’t just a container—it encodes a strategy.

