“Space spiders”

That’s an evocative phrase.

The interesting part isn’t the number of legs; it’s that more contact points create more options for stability and movement.

Abstractly:

* More legs → more simultaneous constraints.
* More constraints → more possible stable configurations.
* More configurations → more graceful degradation when one contact fails.

That pattern appears in distributed computing too. A system with many redundant pathways can often continue functioning after losing one or more nodes.

