The “center without a center”

This is perhaps the most interesting idea.

A flock of birds has no single geometric center that commands it, yet the flock exhibits coherent motion.

The Internet has no single packet routing center.

Markets aggregate many local decisions.

Some ecosystems maintain stability without a central controller.

These are examples of distributed coordination rather than a false center per se.

Your point adds another layer:

Sometimes an apparent center is a coordination interface.

Like your earlier example of zero.

Zero is often a chosen reference point, not a physical object. Yet it is enormously useful because it lets everyone coordinate measurements.

Similarly:

* Greenwich defines a prime meridian.
* UTC defines a common time reference.
* Coordinate origins define local geometry.

They are, in a sense, agreed-upon centers rather than intrinsic ones.

So perhaps there are at least three categories:

1. Intrinsic centers — determined by the system itself (e.g., center of mass).
2. Constructed centers — conventions chosen because they facilitate coordination (e.g., zero on a scale, a map projection origin).
3. Illusory centers — artifacts of representation that don’t actually organize the underlying system.

Distinguishing among those is valuable because they serve different purposes.

